databases — the complete foundation relational and nosql database fundamentals, sql from scratch, mysql, postgresql, mssql, oracle, sqlite, mongodb, redis, and cassandra — with red team perspectives on enumeration, default credentials, privilege escalation, credential extraction, and sql injection for every major engine. learn databases sql mysql postgresql mssql mongodb redis sqli red-team fundamentals every application stores state somewhere. behind almost every web app, every enterprise system, and every internal tool is a database — and databases are goldmines. they hold credentials, pii, business logic, and often provide paths to operating system command execution.

this guide covers database theory from first principles, sql as a language, every major database engine you'll encounter, and the offensive angle on each one — from default credentials and enumeration through privilege escalation and code execution. database fundamentals a **database** is an organised collection of structured data with a mechanism for efficient storage, retrieval, and manipulation. a **database management system (dbms)** is the software layer sitting between the raw data and applications — it handles concurrency, transactions, permissions, and query optimisation. data models core relational concepts **table** — a named grid of rows and columns. each column has a defined data type. each row is one record.

**primary key** — a column (or combination) that uniquely identifies every row. no duplicates, no nulls.

**foreign key** — a column in one table that references the primary key of another. enforces referential integrity.

**index** — a data structure that speeds up reads on a column. trade-off: faster reads, slower writes, more storage.

**schema** — the structure of a database: tables, column names, types, constraints, relationships. some databases are schema-on-write (relational), others schema-on-read (nosql).

**transaction** — a unit of work that either fully succeeds or fully rolls back. guarantees acid properties: normalisation normalisation eliminates data redundancy by splitting data into related tables:

- **1nf** — no repeating groups, each cell holds one value
- **2nf** — 1nf + no partial dependencies on composite key
- **3nf** — 2nf + no transitive dependencies

in practice, most well-designed oltp databases target 3nf. analytical databases (data warehouses) often *denormalise* intentionally for read performance. sql — structured query language sql is the standard language for relational databases. dialects vary between engines (mysql, postgresql, mssql all have extensions) but the core is identical. data definition language (ddl) -- create a database
create database shop;
use shop;  -- mysql/mssql syntax
-- postgresql: \c shop

-- create a table
create table users (
    id          int          not null auto_increment,  -- mysql
    -- id       serial       not null,                  -- postgresql
    -- id       int identity(1,1) not null,             -- mssql
    username    varchar(50)  not null unique,
    email       varchar(255) not null,
    password    varchar(255) not null,
    created_at  datetime     default current_timestamp,
    is_admin    boolean      default false,
    primary key (id)
);

-- alter table
alter table users add column last_login datetime;
alter table users drop column last_login;
alter table users modify column email varchar(320);

-- drop
drop table if exists users;
drop database shop;

-- truncate (delete all rows, keep structure)
truncate table users;

-- indexes
create index idx_email on users(email);
create unique index idx_username on users(username);
drop index idx_email on users;  -- mysql data manipulation language (dml) -- insert
insert into users (username, email, password) values
  ('admin', 'admin@site.com', 'hashed_pw'),
  ('john',  'john@site.com',  'hashed_pw2');

-- select
select * from users;
select username, email from users;
select username from users where is_admin = true;
select * from users where username = 'admin' and is_admin = 1;
select * from users order by created_at desc;
select * from users order by created_at desc limit 10;
select * from users order by created_at desc limit 10 offset 20;

-- update
update users set is_admin = true where username = 'john';
update users set password = 'new_hash', email = 'new@email.com' where id = 3;

-- delete
delete from users where id = 5;
delete from users where created_at < '2020-01-01'; where clause operators where id = 1
where id != 1  -- or <>
where id > 5
where id >= 5
where id between 5 and 10
where username in ('admin', 'root', 'administrator')
where username not in ('guest')
where username like 'a%'      -- starts with a
where username like '%admin%' -- contains admin
where username like 'a___'    -- a + exactly 3 chars
where email is null
where email is not null
where is_admin = true and email is not null
where id = 1 or id = 2
where not is_admin = true aggregate functions select count(*) from users;
select count(distinct email) from users;
select max(id), min(id), avg(id), sum(id) from users;

-- group by
select is_admin, count(*) as total
from users
group by is_admin;

-- having — filter after group by
select department, count(*) as total
from users
group by department
having count(*) > 5; joins -- tables: users (id, username) and orders (id, user_id, product)

-- inner join — only rows with match in both tables
select u.username, o.product
from users u
inner join orders o on u.id = o.user_id;

-- left join — all users, orders if they exist
select u.username, o.product
from users u
left join orders o on u.id = o.user_id;

-- right join — all orders, user if exists
select u.username, o.product
from users u
right join orders o on u.id = o.user_id;

-- full outer join — all rows from both
select u.username, o.product
from users u
full outer join orders o on u.id = o.user_id;  -- postgresql/mssql

-- cross join — cartesian product (every combination)
select u.username, p.product_name
from users u
cross join products p;

-- self join
select e.name as employee, m.name as manager
from employees e
join employees m on e.manager_id = m.id; subqueries and ctes -- subquery in where
select username from users
where id in (select user_id from orders where total > 1000);

-- subquery in from (derived table)
select sub.username, sub.order_count
from (
    select u.username, count(o.id) as order_count
    from users u left join orders o on u.id = o.user_id
    group by u.username
) sub
where sub.order_count > 5;

-- cte (common table expression) — cleaner than nested subqueries
with active_users as (
    select id, username from users where last_login > now() - interval 30 day
),
rich_users as (
    select user_id from orders group by user_id having sum(total) > 5000
)
select a.username
from active_users a
join rich_users r on a.id = r.user_id;

-- recursive cte (useful for hierarchical data like ad org charts)
with recursive org as (
    select id, name, manager_id from employees where manager_id is null
    union all
    select e.id, e.name, e.manager_id from employees e
    join org o on e.manager_id = o.id
)
select * from org; views, stored procedures, triggers -- view — saved query, acts like a read-only table
create view admin_users as
    select id, username, email from users where is_admin = true;

select * from admin_users;
drop view admin_users;

-- stored procedure (mysql)
delimiter //
create procedure getuserbyname(in p_username varchar(50))
begin
    select * from users where username = p_username;
end //
delimiter ;
call getuserbyname('admin');

-- trigger — fires on insert/update/delete
create trigger before_user_insert
before insert on users
for each row
    set new.created_at = now(); mysql / mariadb mysql is the world's most popular open-source relational database. mariadb is a community fork with identical syntax and protocol-level compatibility. you'll encounter it behind most php web apps, wordpress, drupal, and a huge proportion of self-hosted services. default port: 3306 installation and basic usage # install
apt install mysql-server
systemctl start mysql

# secure installation (change root password, remove test dbs)
mysql_secure_installation

# connect
mysql -u root -p
mysql -u root -ppassw0rd
mysql -h 10.10.10.1 -u root -p
mysql -h 10.10.10.1 -p 3306 -u root -p

# non-interactive queries
mysql -u root -ppassw0rd -e 'select version();'
mysql -u root -ppassw0rd dbname -e 'select * from users;' essential mysql commands -- show everything
show databases;
use database_name;
show tables;
describe tablename;
show columns from tablename;
show create table tablename\g

-- users and privileges
select user, host, authentication_string from mysql.user;
show grants for 'username'@'localhost';
grant all privileges on *.* to 'user'@'%' identified by 'password';
grant all privileges on *.* to 'user'@'%' with grant option;
flush privileges;

-- user management
create user 'user'@'%' identified by 'password';
alter user 'root'@'localhost' identified by 'newpassword';
drop user 'username'@'localhost';

-- import / export
mysqldump -u root -p dbname > backup.sql
mysql -u root -p dbname < backup.sql
mysqldump -u root -p --all-databases > all_dbs.sql key mysql configuration file /etc/mysql/mysql.conf.d/mysqld.cnf   # ubuntu/debian
/etc/my.cnf                          # centos/rhel

# critical settings to check:
bind-address = 127.0.0.1   # restrict to localhost (good)
bind-address = 0.0.0.0     # exposed to network (check during recon)
skip-grant-tables          # no password required — critical misconfiguration
local-infile = 1           # file read/write capability (offensive) red team: mysql enumeration # nmap service detection
nmap -sv -p 3306 target
nmap -p 3306 --script mysql-info target
nmap -p 3306 --script mysql-empty-password target
nmap -p 3306 --script mysql-brute --script-args brute.mode=user target
nmap -p 3306 --script mysql-databases --script-args mysql-databases.credentials=root: target

